As is well known, TNP, which contains benzene ring and hydroxyl group, can easily generate picrate anion in aqueous medium [43]. In contrast, the CTA-CDs contain aromatic rings, quaternary ammonium groups and amino groups on the surface. Therefore, the molecular interactions such as electrostatic and hydrogen bonding interactions between the hydroxyl group of TNP and CTA-CDs, and π−π interaction between the benzene ring of TNP and aromatic ring system of CTA-CDs, are formed, which lead to the fluorescence quenching of the CTA-CDs (Fig. 6
                        ). To confirm the electrostatic interaction, a fluorescence quenching experiment was performed with some phenol derivatives, such as nitrophenol (NP) and dinitrophenol (DNP). As shown in Fig. 7
                        a, the fluorescence quenching response of the CTA-CDs towards analytes in aqueous phase follows the order of TNP > DNP > NP, which is in accordance with the order of their acidity [44]. Since electrostatic interaction from acid-base surface functionalization of the CTA-CDs is an important factor, the pH effect was studied as shown in Fig. 7b. The fluorescence quenching efficiency increases from pH 2 to 6.5 and then declined at high pH. The possible reason is that higher pH can increase the deprotonation of TNP, while lower pH could benefit the protonation of the CTA-CDs [29]. In addition, the π−π interaction between the benzene ring of TNP and aromatic ring system of CTA-CDs can be well-verified by a red shift in the fluorescence intensity of upon the addition of high concentrations of TNP into the CTA-CDs (Fig. 4c) [45].
